    GPT‑4‑scale (1.8T params) → 7.2 TB VRAM
    Claude Opus (~6T params) → 24 TB VRAM
    require this much of VRAM to run inference
    NVIDIA H100 NVL (2024–2026 era)
        ~94 GB usable FP16-equivalent HBM per GPU
        FP32 effectively halves usable params → ~47 GB FP32 effective capacity
    For Claude‑scale 6T params:
        24 TB = 24000 GB
        24000 / 47 ≈ 510 GPUs
    LLMs have compute cost roughly:
        FLOPs ≈ 2 × parameters × sequence_length
    For a 1.8T model generating 1 token:
        FLOPs ≈ 3.6e12 FLOPs ≈ 3.6 TFLOPs/token
    Serving 10 concurrent users at 2 tokens/sec each = 20 tokens/s:
       total = 20 × 3.6 TFLOPs ≈ 72 TFLOPs/s
    A single H100 does ~60–90 TFLOPs FP32 (depending on exact spec).
    Thus, compute‑wise, 1 H100 could theoretically handle 10 users.
    But memory scaling dominates, so you still need 150 GPUs to hold the model.
    To serve a model split over 150+ GPUs, you need:

    NVLink/NVSwitch fabric
    ~900 GB/s intra‑cluster bandwidth
    Extremely low‑latency topology (similar to GPT‑4 training clusters)

